{
  "doc_id": "27594",
  "text": "In addition to MHCI proteins, myelin proteins including Nogo-A, OMgp and MAG have been shown to bind to PirB [CITATION_1] . These ligand-receptor interactions elicit growth cone collapse in vitro [CITATION_2] , and possibly in vivo [CITATION_3] . In the context of learning and plasticity, multiple independent studies have implicated all three myelin based proteins in negative regulation of ocular dominance plasticity [CITATION_4] , learning processes during fear extinction [CITATION_5] , and synaptic plasticity [CITATION_6] in adult animals. Even though most of these effects seem to be mediated via Nogo-receptor 1 (NGR1) [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , an OMgp-PirB interaction has been implicated in the negative regulation of hippocampal LTP in adult mice [CITATION_10] . It would be interesting to know if Nogo-A, OMgp, or MAG levels are regulated by neural activity, as is the case for the MHC class I ligands. Together, our current findings suggest a model (Fig. S11 ) in which PirB signaling is modulated by activity-dependent changes in MHCI levels, which in turn affect intracellular signaling cascades downstream of NMDA receptors required for LTD and eCB production and release.",
